          <h2>Extension of limitation period on account of COVID-19 wouldn’t apply to statutory period for condoning delay: SC</h2>
          <amp-img src="file:///C:/Users/User/Desktop/Caro%202020/This_week_Newsletter/Date_Due_SC.svg"
              width="100" height="120"
              layout="responsive">
          </amp-img>
          <p>The main contention of the Appellant was that the NCLAT failed to take note of the lockdown as well as the order passed by the Supreme Court in a suo motu writ petition on March 23, 2020 extending the period of limitation for filing any proceeding with effect from March 15, 2020 until further orders.</p>
        </amp-story-grid-layer>
      </amp-story-page>

      <!-- End of page-6-->

      <!-- Start of page-7-->
       
       <amp-story-page id="page3">
        <amp-story-grid-layer template="vertical">
          <h2>Extension of time limit for issuing an invoice for export of goods under sale on approval basis</h2>
          <amp-img src="file:///C:/Users/User/Desktop/Caro%202020/This_week_Newsletter/Export_Import.svg"
              width="100" height="120"
              layout="responsive">
          </amp-img>
          <p>As per sub-section (7) of section 31 of the CGST Act, where the goods being sent or taken on approval for sale or return are removed before the supply takes place, the invoice shall be issued before or at the time of supply or six months from the date of removal, whichever is earlier.</p>
        </amp-story-grid-layer>
      </amp-story-page>

      <!-- End of Slide 7-->

      <!-- Start of Slide 8-->
      <amp-story-page id="page3">
        <amp-story-grid-layer template="vertical">
          <h2>Late fee waiver for composition taxpayers</h2>
          <amp-img src="file:///C:/Users/User/Desktop/Caro%202020/This_week_Newsletter/Late-fees.svg"
              width="100" height="120"
              layout="responsive">
          </amp-img>
          <p>This relaxation is available if Form GSTR-4 (Quarterly Return) is filed between September 22, 2020 and October 31, 2020, for the quarters from July 2017 to March 2019. Of the late fee of Rs 500, Rs 250 will go towards CGST and the remaining Rs 250 towards SGST.</p>
        </amp-story-grid-layer>
      </amp-story-page>
      <!-- End of Slide 8-->

      <!-- Start of Slide 9-->
